  "slug": "roast-crown-of-lamb",
  "title": "Roast Crown of Lamb",
  "subtitle": "Two French-trimmed racks fashioned into a crown, roasted pink",
  "excerpt": "A crown of lamb is two French-trimmed racks bent into a ring with the bones pointing upward, filled with a herb or apricot stuffing, and roasted at high heat to a blush-pink centre. It is a showpiece that takes less skill than its appearance suggests.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Traditional British celebratory roasting. Jane Grigson, English Food (1974): crown of lamb assembly and stuffing options. Delia Smith, Complete Cookery Course (1978): French-trimmed rack preparation. Cross-referenced across multiple sources.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "A ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "crown roast",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr2xet0001dgv4suq3ztg5"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " is assembled from two racks that have been ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "French-trimmed",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr2xe60000dgv42c9lgkw1"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " by the butcher. The difficulty lies in the assembly, not the cooking; the roasting itself is a short affair at 220°C to an internal temperature of 58°C for pink, 62°C for medium. Ask your butcher to Frenchthe racks; assembling the crown yourself from pre-prepared racks takes about 10 minutes.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The stuffing fills the cavity in the centre of the crown, bakes inside the ring, and slices out with each cutlet. A simple mixture of breadcrumbs, dried apricot, and herbs works well; it contrasts with the richness of the lamb without competing with it.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "What you need",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
