      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Assemble the crown",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Stand both racks bone-side outward in a circle, flesh facing inward. Use kitchen twine to tie the crown securely at two points around the circumference, pulling the ends of the racks together until the circle holds. Wrap foil around the exposed bone tips to prevent scorching. Brush all surfaces with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{olive-oil}} of olive oil",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and season with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ".",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Fill and roast",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Mix the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{breadcrumbs-fresh}} of breadcrumbs",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " with the chopped apricots, parsley, rosemary leaves, and melted butter. Season and pack loosely into the crown cavity. Heat the oven to 220°C (200°C fan). Roast for 25-35 minutes until the eye of the rack reads 58°C for pink, 62°C for medium-pink.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Rest and carve",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Remove the foil from the bones, transfer the crown to a warm board, and rest for 15 minutes. Cut away the twine. Spoon the stuffing out first, then cut down between the ribs to produce individual cutlets. Deglaze the roasting pan with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-beef}} of beef stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and strain the gravy into a warm jug.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Tie at three points rather than two, and ask the butcher to score the chine bone slightly to help the racks bend.",
              "cause": "Racks not tied tightly enough, or the bones are too short to hold the arc",
              "symptom": "The crown falls apart when the racks meet"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Fold a double layer of foil and press firmly onto the tips. Remove for the last 5 minutes only if you want colour on the bones.",
              "cause": "Foil slipped or was too thin",
              "symptom": "Bone tips are scorched despite foil"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Pack more firmly. A small ramekin placed in the cavity before filling can hold the shape during roasting, then removed when the stuffing sets.",
              "cause": "Stuffing packed too loosely",
              "symptom": "Stuffing falls out during roasting"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Probe from the top down into the thick part of each rack's eye, not the thinner outer edge.",
              "cause": "Probe was at the outer wall rather than the inner eye",
              "symptom": "Outer cutlets overcooked while inner ones are rare"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The crown of lamb became a feature of the British celebratory table in the mid-twentieth century, appearing in Constance Spry's menus and later in Delia Smith's party repertoire. It suits Easter and spring entertaining, and the visual impact justifies the modest extra effort in assembly. Each guest receives two or three cutlets with a spoonful of stuffing and the pan gravy.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
